                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="25874" author="david_geary" created="Thu, 30 Aug 2007 21:28:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;On further investigation there are other issues with the insert method. If you try to insert more than one record before storing the acl it can cause a null pointer at:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;if (ace.getId().equals(aceId))&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;in getAceOffset as it might try to check the one you just inserted (with a null id)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In fact there seems no way to build up a list in the correct order on a new acl as all the ids will be null.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;maybe this method should allow the use of indexes instead?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="34391" author="balex" created="Sat, 5 Apr 2008 07:45:06 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Refactored MutableAcl and AuditableAcl interfaces to use indexes instead of AccessControlEntry.getId() as the key for insertAce, updateAce, deleteAce and updateAuditing operations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Updated AclImpl accordingly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To insert an ACE at the end of the ACE list, use acl.insertAce(acl.getEntries().length, ....). To insert an ACE at the start of the ACE list, use acl.insertAce(0, ....).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Modified tests to use the new approach with success. Also updated the Contacts and DMS samples accordingly. Their tests pass.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;SVN commit revision number 2872.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
